trick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hotham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire): habitational name usually from Hotham (East Yorkshire), but occasionally perhaps also from Holtham in Legsby (Lincolnshire). The East Yorkshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hōdum</i>, dative plural form of <i>hōd</i> ‘shelter’, while the origin of the Lincolnshire placename is uncertain. Compare   Holtham  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Holtham","meanings":["English:","habitational name from a place so named or a topographic name for someone who lived ‘(at the) enclosure in the wood’, from Middle English <i>holt</i> ‘wood, grove’ + <i>ham</i> ‘enclosure’ (Old English <i>holt</i> + <i>hamm</i>). Compare   Haltom   and   Holtom  .","variant of   Hotham  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Hotham was born about 1100. He married Mrs. William de HOTHAM about 1132, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1100–":"umbes 1100–Surnud","1104–Female":"1104–Surnud","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1100–Male":"1100–Surnud","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1175":"1175","about 1132":"umbes 1132","about 1100":"umbes 1100","about 1133":"umbes 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1100–":"noin 1100–Kuollut","1104–Female":"1104–Kuollut","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1100–Male":"1100–Kuollut","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1175":"1175","about 1132":"noin 1132","about 1100":"noin 1100","about 1133":"noin 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1100–":"environ 1100–Décédé","1104–Female":"1104–Décédée","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1100–Male":"1100–Décédé","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1175":"1175","about 1132":"environ 1132","about 1100":"environ 1100","about 1133":"environ 1133","England":"Angleterre","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"William de Hotham est né environ 1100. Il a épousé Mrs. William de HOTHAM environ 1132, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"about 1100–":"um 1100–Verstorben","1104–Female":"1104–Verstorben","1133–1175":"1133–1175","1100–Male":"1100–Verstorben","1104":"1104","1100":"1100","1133":"1133","1175":"1175","about 1132":"um 1132","about 1100":"um 1100","about 1133":"um 1133","England":"England","Howden, Yorkshire, England":"Howden, Yorkshire, England","lifeSummary":"William de Hotham wurde um 1100 geboren. Er hat um 1132 in England Mrs. William de HOTHAM geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"a